TY  - JOUR
T1  - Labor Market Returns to the GED Using Regression Discontinuity Analysis
AU  - Jepsen, Christopher
AU  - Mueser, Peter
AU  - Troske, Kenneth
Y1  - 2016/05/05
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/686245
DO  - 10.1086/686245
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 621
EP  - 649
VL  - 124
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We evaluate returns to General Educational Development (GED) certification for high school dropouts using state administrative data. We apply a fuzzy regression discontinuity method to account for test takers retaking the test. For women we find that GED certification has no statistically significant effect on either employment or earnings. For men we find a significant increase in earnings in the second year after taking the test but no impact in subsequent years. GED certification increases postsecondary school enrollment by 4?8 percentage points. Our results differ from regression discontinuity approaches that fail to account for test retaking.
AB  - We evaluate returns to General Educational Development (GED) certification for high school dropouts using state administrative data. We apply a fuzzy regression discontinuity method to account for test takers retaking the test. For women we find that GED certification has no statistically significant effect on either employment or earnings. For men we find a significant increase in earnings in the second year after taking the test but no impact in subsequent years. GED certification increases postsecondary school enrollment by 4?8 percentage points. Our results differ from regression discontinuity approaches that fail to account for test retaking.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/686245
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/686245
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Gender Roles and Medical Progress
AU  - Albanesi, Stefania
AU  - Olivetti, Claudia
Y1  - 2016/05/03
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/686035
DO  - 10.1086/686035
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 650
EP  - 695
VL  - 124
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Maternal mortality was the second-largest cause of death for women in childbearing years until the mid-1930s in the United States. For each death, 20 times as many mothers suffered pregnancy-related conditions, which made it hard for them to engage in market work. Between 1930 and 1960 there was a remarkable improvement in maternal health. We argue that this development, by enabling women to reconcile work and motherhood, was essential for the joint rise in women?s labor force participation and fertility over this period. We also show that the diffusion of infant formula played an important auxiliary role.
AB  - Maternal mortality was the second-largest cause of death for women in childbearing years until the mid-1930s in the United States. For each death, 20 times as many mothers suffered pregnancy-related conditions, which made it hard for them to engage in market work. Between 1930 and 1960 there was a remarkable improvement in maternal health. We argue that this development, by enabling women to reconcile work and motherhood, was essential for the joint rise in women?s labor force participation and fertility over this period. We also show that the diffusion of infant formula played an important auxiliary role.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/686035
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/686035
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Social Effects of Ethnic Diversity at the Local Level: A Natural Experiment with Exogenous Residential Allocation
AU  - Algan, Yann
AU  - Hémet, Camille
AU  - Laitin, David D.
Y1  - 2016/05/04
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2016/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/686010
DO  - 10.1086/686010
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 696
EP  - 733
VL  - 124
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Relying on diversity measures computed at the apartment block level under conditions of exogenous allocation of public housing in France, this paper identifies the effects of ethnic diversity on social relationships and housing quality. Housing Survey data reveal that diversity induces social anomie. Through the channel of anomie, diversity accounts for the inability of residents to sanction others for vandalism and to act collectively to demand proper building maintenance. However, anomie also lowers opportunities for violent confrontations, which are not related to diversity.
AB  - Relying on diversity measures computed at the apartment block level under conditions of exogenous allocation of public housing in France, this paper identifies the effects of ethnic diversity on social relationships and housing quality. Housing Survey data reveal that diversity induces social anomie. Through the channel of anomie, diversity accounts for the inability of residents to sanction others for vandalism and to act collectively to demand proper building maintenance. However, anomie also lowers opportunities for violent confrontations, which are not related to diversity.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/686010
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/686010
Y2  - 2024/03/20
